The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A fire broke out on the first floor of a hotel in Chowringhee Lane on Sunday morning. According to fire department officials, boarders in the dormitory noticed smoke emanating from a cubicle around 8 am. Three fire tenders from the Free School Street fire station rushed to the hotel at 13, Chowringhee Lane, in the New Market police station area. 

 f the 22 people trapped on the first floor, nine were rescued using a ladder. The rest were evacuated through the staircase. The fire fighters doused the blaze in 40 minutes. 

 o one was injured, though two cubicles, air-conditioners, television sets and furniture were gutted. The cause of the fire is yet to be known.

 Entry fee of Rs 2 per head will be charged at the Eden Gardens from Monday. Somenath Mukherjee, deputy conservator of forests, said on Sunday that visitors to the 15-acre green will be charged between 8 am and 5.30 pm.

 A passenger was arrested at Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose International Airport on Sunday, allegedly for attempting to smuggle out US dollars. Dinesh Gupta was to fly to Bangkok. According to airport officials, $33,000 (around Rs 15 lakh) was seized from him.

 Members of the Howrah Chamber of Commerce will convey their grievances to chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee on Tuesday. Bhattacharjee is scheduled to attend the Chamber?s annual general meeting that day. 

 We will draw the chief minister?s attention to our various problems,? said Sankar Kumar Sanyal, Chamber president. 

 A 13-year-old girl suffered head injuries after being hit by a private car on SP Mukherjee Road on Sunday afternoon. 

 ccording to police, the car knocked down Tuki Maity when she was about to cross the road near the SP Mukherjee-Kabir Road intersection. She has been admitted to Bangur Hospital in a critical condition. The vehicle has been impounded.

 Sambhu Debnath, 16, fell off an overcrowded local train on the Sealdah-Barasat route on Sunday afternoon. He was standing at the door and leaning out. Sambhu?s grip slackened after he was hit by a signal post. He was taken to Barasat State General Hospital, where he was declared dead. 

 The Howrah Traffic Awareness Society has appealed to transport minister Subhas Chakraborty to enforce a particular colour for all motor training cars. Society secretary Alok Chakraborty said on Sunday that different colours of the training cars create confusion among police and learners. 

 Two unidentified persons were killed after a truck knocked them down on National Highway 6 in Liluah, Howrah, on Sunday afternoon. Police said the victims were pedestrians. The mishap took place when they were crossing the road. The bodies have been sent for post-mortem. The truck has been impounded, though the driver managed to flee. 

 Sevac, an NGO, has been chosen by the state government to conduct a training programme for nurses on mental health. The programme begins on Tuesday in Barasat. 

